    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Tech concerns about existential risks may border on fearmongering, but history offers ample evidence the opposite—that under-regulation breeds disaster. The Luddites burned factories in protest against technological unemployment; less severe consequences loom in AI's future. Tech advocates' libertarian views might tout innovation but ignore hazards likened to unfettered market capitalism before the 1930s' breadline crisis. So, while the existentialist argument might seem hypothetical now, they’re barking up the right tree, aiming to zero in on AI's firepower we create with insufficient foresight. It's better to face concrete misuse than grapple with an economical dystopia. Deep regulation now could prevent radical tech horrors that turn our potential utopia into a dystopian nightmare. In my view, the tech community, while optimistic, may do well to temper their free-market enthusiasm with precautionary foresight, akin to societal safety nets. After all, if no one thought of self-preservation before, our temperate way forward could still save us from ecological and technological self-destruction—the ultimate job creation isn't maintaining life but preserving the world for jobs. I argue for guided AI development, not limiting innovation, ensuring we harness perks efficiently and safely. Moreover, a regulated tech domain could",
      "source": "target",
